	        	<div class=3D"post-content">
		        <div class=3D"entry-content">

                                        <p>Gauge describes <strong>the size=
 of knitted stitches</strong>.&nbsp; It is a measure of how large the stitc=
hes are, and is defined by how many stitches and rows or rounds there are i=
n one inch (2.5cm) or 4 inches (10cm) of knitted fabric. Why is this import=
ant?</p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><a class=3D"wp-block-table-of-contents__entry" href=3D"https://blog.tin=
canknits.com/2013/08/17/gauge/#every-knitter-is-unique-when-it-comes-to-gau=
ge">Every knitter is unique (when it comes to gauge)</a></li>



<li><a class=3D"wp-block-table-of-contents__entry" href=3D"https://blog.tin=
canknits.com/2013/08/17/gauge/#why-does-gauge-matter-what-is-it-for">What i=
s gauge and why does it matter?</a></li>



<li><a class=3D"wp-block-table-of-contents__entry" href=3D"https://blog.tin=
canknits.com/2013/08/17/gauge/#what-is-a-gauge-swatch">The gauge swatch</a>=
</li>



<li><a class=3D"wp-block-table-of-contents__entry" href=3D"https://blog.tin=
canknits.com/2013/08/17/gauge/#so-you-ve-knit-your-swatch-time-for-some-mea=
surements">Measuring your gauge</a></li>



<li><a class=3D"wp-block-table-of-contents__entry" href=3D"https://blog.tin=
canknits.com/2013/08/17/gauge/#once-you-ve-measured-gauge-what-s-the-next-s=
tep">Once you=E2=80=99ve measured gauge, what=E2=80=99s the next step?</a><=
/li>



<li><a class=3D"wp-block-table-of-contents__entry" href=3D"https://blog.tin=
canknits.com/2013/08/17/gauge/#should-i-go-up-a-needle-size-or-down-a-needl=
e-size">Should I go up a needle size or down a needle size? </a></li>



<li><a class=3D"wp-block-table-of-contents__entry" href=3D"https://blog.tin=
canknits.com/2013/08/17/gauge/#why-bother-checking-gauge-does-a-small-diffe=
rence-in-gauge-really-matter">Why bother checking gauge=E2=80=A6 does a sma=
ll difference in gauge really matter?</a></li>



<li><a class=3D"wp-block-table-of-contents__entry" href=3D"https://blog.tin=
canknits.com/2013/08/17/gauge/#but-sometimes-gauge-just-doesn-t-matter">But=
 sometimes=E2=80=A6 gauge just doesn=E2=80=99t matter</a></li>
</ol>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"every-knitter-is-unique-when-it-comes-=
to-gauge">Every knitter is unique (when it comes to gauge)</h2>



<p>Every knitter is different =E2=80=93 we hold our needles and yarn slight=
ly differently, we are more tense or relaxed as we work. This means is that=
 if I knit a square using aran weight yarn and 5mm needles, and Alexa knits=
 a square using exactly the same yarn and needles, the two squares of fabri=
c will likely be slightly different sizes because Alexa and I have differen=
t tensions.</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-full"><img data-tf-not-load=3D"1" data=
-recalc-dims=3D"1" fetchpriority=3D"high" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"600" =
height=3D"237" data-attachment-id=3D"2242" data-permalink=3D"https://blog.t=
incanknits.com/2013/08/17/gauge/gauge-pattern/" data-orig-file=3D"https://i=
0.wp.com/blog.tincanknits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/gauge-pattern.jpg?=
fit=3D600%2C237&amp;ssl=3D1" data-orig-size=3D"600,237" data-comments-opene=
d=3D"1" data-image-meta=3D"{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit=
&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&qu=
