esize=3D600%2C237&amp;ssl=3D1" alt=3D"annotated excerpt from a knitting pat=
tern" class=3D"wp-image-2242"><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">An e=
xample of how yarn, gauge, and suggested needles are listed in a knitting p=
attern. Needle sizes given are just a SUGGESTION =E2=80=93 you need to swat=
ch, and change needles until you achieve the gauge stated in the pattern.</=
figcaption></figure>



<p>If you like free knitting patterns, and helpful tutorials like this one,=
 <a href=3D"https://mailchi.mp/tincanknits/emails">sign up for our email up=
dates=E2=80=A6 and tell us what you=E2=80=99d like to learn</a> =E2=80=93 A=
lexa and I are here to help!</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"why-does-gauge-matter-what-is-it-for">=
Why does gauge matter=E2=80=A6 what is it FOR?</h2>



<p>The gauge stated on knitting patterns acts as a universal equalizer =E2=
=80=93 it allows different knitters to follow the same pattern and achieve =
the desired size.</p>



<p class=3D"has-pale-ocean-gradient-background has-background has-medium-fo=
nt-size">If a sweater pattern was simply written for worsted weight yarn an=
d 5mm needles, then everyone=E2=80=99s sweaters would come out differently =
=E2=80=93 <strong>there would be no way to predict finished size</strong>.<=
/p>



<p>So instead of simply casting on with the needle size suggested in the pa=
ttern, when knitting garments you must make a =E2=80=98gauge swatch=E2=80=
=99, to confirm which needle size you will need to achieve the pattern gaug=
e.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"what-is-a-gauge-swatch">What is a gaug=
e swatch?</h2>



<p>A swatch is a little piece of knitted fabric, usually about 6=E2=80=B3 s=
quare-ish or round-ish. Making a gauge swatch gives you a bit of an insight=
 into what your finished garment will look like. It shows you how dense wil=
l the fabric be, what gauge you achieve with a given needle size, and what =
the fabric will look like close up.</p>



<p><strong>Rounds or rows?</strong> If you are working on an item that is w=
orked back and forth in rows, like a scarf or a cardigan, you will have a r=
ow gauge. If you are working on an item that is knit in the round, like a h=
at or a pullover, you will have a round gauge. </p>



<p>Why does this matter? Knitter=E2=80=99s gauges (both stitch gauge and ro=
w/round gauge) in rows and rounds can differ, even if we are talking about =
the same knitter on the same size needles. </p>



<p class=3D"has-pale-ocean-gradient-background has-background has-medium-fo=
nt-size"><strong>So, if you are going to be working in rows, your swatch sh=
ould be in rows. If you are working in rounds, your swatch should be in rou=
nds.</strong> </p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"making-a-flat-gauge-swatch">Making a f=
lat gauge swatch</h2>



<p>To make a flat gauge swatch, in rows, I typically cast on about 6=E2=80=
=B3 worth of stitches using the needle size suggested by the pattern. If th=
e pattern gauge is 5 sts / inch <em>(5 sts x 6=E2=80=B3 =3D 30)</em> then c=
ast on approximately 30 stitches.&nbsp; Knit a little square starting with =
a few rows of garter stitch, then working a section of stockinette stitch w=
ith little garter borders, then finishing with a bit more garter stitch <em=
>(the garter edging makes the square lie flat, because stockinette stitch o=
n its own curls)</em>.</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image aligncenter"><a href=3D"https://i0.wp.com/b=
log.tincanknits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/tightandloose.jpg"><img load=
ing=3D"lazy" data-recalc-dims=3D"1" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"600" height=
