<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"but-sometimes-gauge-just-doesn-t-matte=
r">But sometimes=E2=80=A6 gauge just doesn=E2=80=99t matter</h2>



<p>There are, of course, projects in which gauge is not very important, bec=
ause fit is less crucial.&nbsp; If you are working a cowl, or a scarf, a sh=
awl, a blanket, or a hat, slight differences in finished size will be less =
important or evident.&nbsp; For the blanket, cowl, and scarf, the finished =
size isn=E2=80=99t too critical. For the hat, there are really only so many=
 stitches so you can only be off by so much. It=E2=80=99s also just a hat s=
o a few hours of knitting to find out it=E2=80=99s too big or small isn=E2=
=80=99t as killer as a sweater<em> (personal experience)</em>. So in these =
cases it is up to you whether making a gauge swatch is worthwhile!</p>



